.TH FZY 1 "2025-07-12" "fzy 1.1"
.SH NAME
fzy \- A fuzzy text selector menu for the terminal.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B fzy
.IR [OPTION]...
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B fzy is a fuzzy text selector/file finder for the terminal using a search
similar to that of TextMate or CmdT.

fzy reads a list of newline-separated items from stdin to be displayed as a
menu in the terminal.
Upon pressing ENTER, the currently selected item is printed to stdout.

Entering text narrows the items using fuzzy matching. Results are sorted using
heuristics for the best match.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-lines =\fILINES\fR
Result lines (default: fill terminal height). If unspecified, uses the terminal height minus the prompt (and optional header, info line, and border rows).
.
.TP
.BR \-H ", " \-\-header =\fIHEADER\fR
String to print as item list header (interactive mode only, between the prompt and the results).
.
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-prompt =\fIPROMPT\fR
Input prompt (default '> ')
.
.TP
.B \-\-info =\fISTYLE\fR
Finder info style: \fBdefault\fR, \fBhidden\fR, \fBinline\fR, or \fBinline-right\fR. \fBdefault\fR is used when \fB\-\-info\fR is omitted: print \fIM\fR/\fIT\fR (no brackets) on its own line below the prompt and above \fB\-\-header\fR (if any). \fBhidden\fR disables that line. \fBinline\fR appends \fB " < \fIM\fR/\fIT\fR\fB"\fR after the query. \fBinline-right\fR right-aligns \fIM\fR/\fIT\fR on the prompt row (no leading \fB<\fR). \fB\-i\fR/\fB\-\-show-info\fR still draws \fB[\fIM\fR/\fIT\fR\fB]\fR after the header.
.
.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-query =\fIQUERY\fR
Use QUERY as the initial search string.
.
.TP
.BR \-e ", " \-\-show-matches =\fIQUERY\fR
Output the sorted matches of QUERY (non-interactive mode; prints to stdout).
.
.TP
.BR \-t ", " \-\-tty =\fITTY\fR
Specify file to use as TTY device (default /dev/tty).
.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-show-scores
Show the scores of each match.
.
.TP
.BR \-0 ", " \-\-read-null
Read input delimited by ASCII NUL characters.
.
.TP
.BR \-j ", " \-\-workers =\fINUM\fR
Use NUM workers for searching. (default is # of CPUs)
.
.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-show-info
Show selection info line.
.
.TP
.B \-\-border
Draw a padded box. Unicode box-drawing characters are used when \fBTERM\fR is not \fBdumb\fR or \fBunknown\fR and any of: the locale charset is UTF-8 (\fBnl_langinfo\fR(\fBCODESET\fR), spelling-insensitive); \fBLC_ALL\fR, \fBLC_CTYPE\fR, or \fBLANG\fR contains \fButf-8\fR or \fB.utf8\fR; or \fBTERM\fR looks like a common UTF-8 terminal (e.g. \fBxterm*\fR, \fBtmux\fR, \fB*256color*\fR). Otherwise \fB+\fR, \fB-\fR, and \fB|\fR. Without \fBLANG\fR/\fBLC_*\fR, libc often reports \fBUS-ASCII\fR even for a UTF-8 terminal; the \fBTERM\fR heuristic covers that. Exporting \fBLANG\fR=\fIxx\fR\fB.UTF-8\fR is still the most reliable fix on odd systems. One space of padding inside each vertical side. Requires at least five terminal columns. Redraws on resize. Border glyphs use gray by default unless overridden with \fB\-\-color\fR \fBborder\fR.
.
.TP
.B \-\-border-label =\fILABEL\fR
Label for the top border (with \fB\-\-border\fR; truncated if too wide). \fILABEL\fR is centered between the corners. Foreground defaults to \fB\-\-color\fR \fBfg\fR (and background to \fBbg\fR); use \fBlabel\fR in \fB\-\-color\fR to set the label color explicitly; horizontal segments stay in the border color.
.
.TP
.B \-\-color =\fISPEC\fR
Colorize with \fBfg\fR\fB:\fR\fIN\fR, \fBbg\fR\fB:\fR\fIN\fR, \fBfg+\fR\fB:\fR\fIN\fR (selected row foreground, bold plus color), \fBbg+\fR\fB:\fR\fIN\fR (selected row background), etc. (comma-separated; \fIN\fR=color-name, \fB0\fR\-\fB255\fR (256-color palette), or \fB#rgb\fR/\fB#rrggbb\fR (24-bit true color)). Other keys: \fBborder\fR, \fBprompt\fR, \fBheader\fR, \fBinfo\fR, \fBlabel\fR (alias \fBborder-label\fR). With colors on (default), the search string is bold; the selected list row uses bold foreground and dark gray background unless overridden via \fBfg+\fR/\fBbg+\fR. Example: \fB\-\-color 'fg+:208,bg+:236,label:132,prompt:146,header:180,bg:235,fg:250'\fR.
.
.TP
.B \-\-no-color
Disable ANSI colors (no default theme and no \fB\-\-color\fR output). A later \fB\-\-color\fR on the same command line turns colors back on.
.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display this help and exit.
.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Output version information and exit.
.
.SH KEYS
.
.TP
.BR "ENTER"
Print the selected item to stdout and exit
.TP
.BR "Ctrl+c, Ctrl+g, Esc"
Exit with status 1, without making a selection.
.TP
.BR "Up Arrow, Ctrl+p, Ctrl+k"
Select the previous item
.TP
.BR "Down Arrow, Ctrl+n, Ctrl+j"
Select the next item
.TP
Tab
Replace the current search string with the selected item
.TP
.BR "Backspace, Ctrl+h"
Delete the character before the cursor
.TP
.BR Ctrl+w
Delete the word before the cursor
.TP
.BR Ctrl+u
Delete the entire line
.
.SH USAGE EXAMPLES
.
.TP
.BR "ls | fzy"
Present a menu of items in the current directory
.TP
.BR "ls | fzy -l 25"
Same as above, but show 25 lines of items
.TP
.BR "vi $(find -type f | fzy)"
List files under the current directory and open the one selected in vi.
.TP
.BR "cd $(find -type d | fzy)"
Present all directories under current path, and change to the one selected.
.TP
.BR "ps aux | fzy | awk '{ print $2 }' | xargs kill"
List running processes, kill the selected process
.TP
.BR "git checkout $(git branch | cut -c 3- | fzy)"
Same as above, but switching git branches.
.SH AUTHOR
John Hawthorn <john.hawthorn@gmail.com>
